                int links = 0;
                int rechts = vec_elements.size() - 1;
                int mitte;
                T midElem;
                int cmpResult;
                //
                index = NOT_SET_int;
                while (links &lt;= rechts) {
                    mitte = links + ((rechts - links) / 2);
                    midElem = vec_elements.elementAt(mitte);
                    cmpResult = comp.compare(midElem, key);
                    if (cmpResult == COMPARE_IDENTICAL) {
                        // Element key gefunden!
                        index = mitte;
                        break; // exit while-loop
                    } else {
                        if (cmpResult &gt; 0) {
                            // im linken Abschnitt weitersuchen
                            rechts = mitte - 1;
                        } else {
                            // midElem &lt; key
                            // im rechten Abschnitt weitersuchen
                            links = mitte + 1;
                        } // end if
                    } // end if
                } // end while

                if (index == NOT_SET_int) {
                    if (rechts &lt; 0)
                        index = rechts;
                    else
                        index = -rechts - 2;
                    // end if
                } // else: found, return index.
            }
                break;
            default:
                throw (new IllegalStateException(
                                &quot;binary search method not implemented&quot;));
        }

        return index;
    }
```

`Vector` implements `List`, so you can use [`Collections.binarySearch(List, T, Comparator)`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Collections.html#binarySearch-java.util.List-T-java.util.Comparator-)

    final Vector&lt;String&gt; vector = new Vector&lt;&gt;();
    vector.add(&quot;foo&quot;);
    vector.add(&quot;bar&quot;);
    vector.sort(Comparator.naturalOrder());
    int fooIndex = Collections.binarySearch(vector, &quot;foo&quot;, Comparator.naturalOrder());

Since the vector in this example uses *natural ordering*, we can also use a simpler overload

    // ...
    int fooIndex = Collections.binarySearch(vector, &quot;foo&quot;);

